00:00:00.770 --> 00:00:03.970
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington D.C.

00:00:18.400 --> 00:00:20.790
&gt;&gt; Catherine Kerst: Well, it's
a pleasure for me to be here.

00:00:20.790 --> 00:00:22.090
&gt;&gt; Anuradha Nehru: Thank you.

00:00:22.090 --> 00:00:23.390
&gt;&gt; Catherine Kerst: Speaking
with you, and I look forward

00:00:23.390 --> 00:00:27.340
to learning more about Kuchipudi
and about your background.

00:00:27.340 --> 00:00:30.050
First, maybe you could
tell us a little bit

00:00:30.050 --> 00:00:34.890
about this classical
dance form from India.

00:00:34.890 --> 00:00:36.190
&gt;&gt; Anuradha Nehru: Sure.

00:00:36.190 --> 00:00:40.120
Kuchipudi is one of eight
classical styles of India,

00:00:40.120 --> 00:00:42.410
and it comes from a southern,

00:00:42.410 --> 00:00:45.740
southeastern state
called Andhra Pradesh.

00:00:45.740 --> 00:00:53.020
And, Kuchipudi gets its name from
a village by the name Kuchipudi

00:00:53.020 --> 00:00:57.230
which is located in Andhra.

00:00:57.230 --> 00:01:01.160
And, Kuchipudi also another
characteristic feature

00:01:01.160 --> 00:01:08.580
about Kuchipudi is that it was
started by an all-male group

00:01:08.580 --> 00:01:14.370
of dancers, or rather one man
by the name of Siddhendra Yogi

00:01:14.370 --> 00:01:18.770
who took a young group, a
group of young Brahman boys

00:01:18.770 --> 00:01:23.790
and started teaching them the
Kuchipudi as we know it today

00:01:23.790 --> 00:01:29.050
which is, which is
about 500 years old.

00:01:29.050 --> 00:01:32.840
Kuchipudi otherwise can be
traced back all the way to well

00:01:32.840 --> 00:01:38.580
over 2000 years ago where,
and we can say this only

00:01:38.580 --> 00:01:45.130 position:56%
because we have evidence from temple
sculptures and also other evidence

00:01:45.130 --> 00:01:49.240
of classical, thriving classical
Indian dance and music culture

00:01:49.240 --> 00:01:55.700
in India from mural
paintings in caves as well as,

00:01:55.700 --> 00:01:59.620
as well as beautiful
sculptures of dancers in temples.

00:01:59.620 --> 00:02:00.920
So, even though we know

00:02:00.920 --> 00:02:06.340
that Kuchipudi originated somewhere
before around 2000 years ago.

00:02:06.340 --> 00:02:07.890
&gt;&gt; Catherine Kerst: That's amazing.

00:02:07.890 --> 00:02:09.860
&gt;&gt; Anuradha Nehru: The
Kuchipudi that we say

00:02:09.860 --> 00:02:13.410
that we practice today comes
from the village of Kuchipudi

00:02:13.410 --> 00:02:21.240 position:56%
which was founded by Siddhendra Yogi
in this village called Kuchipudi.

00:02:21.240 --> 00:02:23.650
I can go on, but I don't.

00:02:23.650 --> 00:02:25.350
&gt;&gt; Catherine Kerst:
I'm curious to know,

00:02:25.350 --> 00:02:29.090
you said there are eight
different classical forms.

00:02:29.090 --> 00:02:34.000 position:56%
What is distinctive about the
Kuchipudi as opposed to these other?

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:35.300
&gt;&gt; Anuradha Nehru: You know,

00:02:35.300 --> 00:02:39.960
all eight Indian classical
dance styles are in,

00:02:39.960 --> 00:02:45.960
draw their inspiration from the
same text called the Natya Shastra,

00:02:45.960 --> 00:02:52.090
and the Natya Shastra was,
is very wide in its scope.

00:02:52.090 --> 00:02:57.260
It's, and it covers chapters,

00:02:57.260 --> 00:03:00.300
there are chapters
dedicated to music and dance.

00:03:00.300 --> 00:03:06.940
It's a 36 chapter book which covers
all aspects of performance art.

00:03:06.940 --> 00:03:11.350
And, so all eight Indian classical
styles draw their inspiration

00:03:11.350 --> 00:03:17.210
from this text, however each
of these styles developed

00:03:17.210 --> 00:03:24.730 position:56%
and interpreted dance based on their
own regional cultural influences.

00:03:24.730 --> 00:03:27.760
And, just as each of
these, each of the states

00:03:27.760 --> 00:03:31.470
in India are pretty
different culturally,

00:03:31.470 --> 00:03:38.760 position:56%
the dance forms reflect that, and so
Kuchipudi as we practice it today,

00:03:38.760 --> 00:03:44.710
as I said before, came from what
Siddhendra Yogi developed 500

00:03:44.710 --> 00:03:46.010
years ago.

00:03:46.010 --> 00:03:50.970
And, because it was an all-male
dance form up until 75 years ago,

00:03:50.970 --> 00:03:58.640
it tends to be a more vigorous
dance form relative to, say,

00:03:58.640 --> 00:04:02.390
Bharatanatyam, Odissi which are
its neighboring dance forms.

00:04:02.390 --> 00:04:13.580 position:56%
The other interesting characteristic
trait of Kuchipudi is that it is,

00:04:13.580 --> 00:04:18.320
it's both, it's got three, I'm
getting very technical here.

00:04:18.320 --> 00:04:22.980
It sits between Tamil
Nadu and Odisha in India,

00:04:22.980 --> 00:04:27.400
and it's a perfect
amalgamation of those two styles.

00:04:27.400 --> 00:04:31.610
For example, Odissi is
a very fluid dance form.

00:04:31.610 --> 00:04:36.520
It's, it literally feels like it,
the dance flows from one's culture

00:04:36.520 --> 00:04:39.200
as opposed to another in movement.

00:04:39.200 --> 00:04:42.720
And, contrasting that,
Bharatanatyam which is

00:04:42.720 --> 00:04:47.950
from Tamil Nadu is a very rigid,

00:04:47.950 --> 00:04:50.880
geometrical dance form
where there are.

00:04:50.880 --> 00:04:55.700
It's highly classical, but
they draw geometric shapes

00:04:55.700 --> 00:04:58.030
in space through dance.

00:04:58.030 --> 00:05:02.960
And, Kuchipudi sits somewhere
between these two where it's fluid,

00:05:02.960 --> 00:05:06.450
at the same time it's
quite structured as well.

00:05:06.450 --> 00:05:07.940
That's the best way
I can describe that.

00:05:07.940 --> 00:05:09.240
&gt;&gt; Catherine Kerst:
That's wonderful.

00:05:09.240 --> 00:05:10.540
&gt;&gt; Anuradha Nehru: Movement.

