00:31:06.380 --> 00:31:10.700
But, we did that, but in
addition to that, we experimented

00:31:10.700 --> 00:31:14.030
with an abstract depiction
of the nine moods.

00:31:14.030 --> 00:31:16.060
And, that was the work
we took to India.

00:31:16.060 --> 00:31:18.930
So, it was with, to Indian music.

00:31:18.930 --> 00:31:23.390
We commissioned that work also
where it was an Indian composer.

00:31:23.390 --> 00:31:27.190 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Catherine Kerst: So, with facial,
I mean, there's a lot of gesture.

00:31:27.190 --> 00:31:29.000 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Anuradha Nehru: A lot of gesture.

00:31:29.000 --> 00:31:33.630
&gt;&gt; Catherine Kerst: And, hand
mudras, and also facial --

00:31:33.630 --> 00:31:34.930
&gt;&gt; Anuradha Nehru: Yes.

00:31:34.930 --> 00:31:36.230
&gt;&gt; Catherine Kerst: Expressions.

00:31:36.230 --> 00:31:37.530
&gt;&gt; Anuradha Nehru: Yeah.

00:31:37.530 --> 00:31:38.830 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Catherine Kerst: You worked with.

00:31:38.830 --> 00:31:40.130
&gt;&gt; Anuradha Nehru: We have
an entire language of gesture

00:31:40.130 --> 00:31:44.300 position:56%
that forms our vocabulary of
movement for us to tell our stories,

00:31:44.300 --> 00:31:47.740
and that's supplemented
with facial expressions.

00:31:47.740 --> 00:31:54.290
Facial expressions is a key
part of storytelling for us.

00:31:54.290 --> 00:31:57.620
We use the combination of
the language of gesture

00:31:57.620 --> 00:32:00.420
as well as facial expressions.

00:32:00.420 --> 00:32:08.780
But, in this work called "Rasa",
we did that, but we extended it to,

00:32:08.780 --> 00:32:14.590
so for say, let's take
sadness, Karunyam.

00:32:14.590 --> 00:32:22.750
We used a story to depict sadness,
and then we continued the work

00:32:22.750 --> 00:32:29.220
by using just movement of
the body to express sadness.

00:32:29.220 --> 00:32:35.070
And, because I, as I said earlier,
I do believe even just the movement

00:32:35.070 --> 00:32:37.810
of the body, the vocabulary

00:32:37.810 --> 00:32:43.840
of the actual entire body
movement itself is very expressive.

00:32:43.840 --> 00:32:47.300
Besides having, in
addition to that language

00:32:47.300 --> 00:32:49.460
of gesture and facial expressions.

00:32:49.460 --> 00:32:54.530
&gt;&gt; Catherine Kerst: So, is there a
difference in performing in Indian

00:32:54.530 --> 00:32:59.660 position:56%
with an Indian audience who has some
concept of the heritage of Kuchipudi

00:32:59.660 --> 00:33:02.060
as opposed to an audience here?

00:33:02.060 --> 00:33:03.360
And, how is that as --

00:33:03.360 --> 00:33:04.660
&gt;&gt; Anuradha Nehru: Yes.

00:33:04.660 --> 00:33:06.180
&gt;&gt; Catherine Kerst: As a
performer and a choreographer?

00:33:06.180 --> 00:33:07.480
&gt;&gt; Anuradha Nehru: Yeah.

00:33:07.480 --> 00:33:09.130
Yeah. It's a very good question.

00:33:09.130 --> 00:33:12.720
I mean, for years, I've
struggled with this.

00:33:12.720 --> 00:33:17.410 position:56%
It's always easier to dance in India
because there's so much context,

00:33:17.410 --> 00:33:19.700
and the audience just gets it.

00:33:19.700 --> 00:33:26.560
They, having, you know, been
brought up in the same culture.

00:33:26.560 --> 00:33:29.880
Performing in America
has been very challenging

00:33:29.880 --> 00:33:33.470 position:56%
because there's so much that's lost.

00:33:33.470 --> 00:33:40.950 position:56%
People don't understand the language
of the poetry, of the lyrics.

00:33:40.950 --> 00:33:43.880
They don't understand,
necessarily, the music itself.

00:33:43.880 --> 00:33:46.250
They don't understand
the language of gestures.

00:33:46.250 --> 00:33:52.270
So, it's a lot was lost, and so
we tried to supplement our dance

00:33:52.270 --> 00:33:57.550
with extensive narratives
or narration, you know,

00:33:57.550 --> 00:34:02.220
just explaining each dance before
dancing it which helped somewhat.

00:34:02.220 --> 00:34:04.040
&gt;&gt; Catherine Kerst: Sure.

00:34:04.040 --> 00:34:09.920
To some extent, and now, more
recently because we've experimented

00:34:09.920 --> 00:34:13.570
with surtitles, I think
that's even more,

00:34:13.570 --> 00:34:16.870
brings Indian dance even closer.

00:34:16.870 --> 00:34:25.360
But, I also do believe that we
could bring Indian dance closer

00:34:25.360 --> 00:34:31.170
to our audiences just, you
know, without necessarily having

00:34:31.170 --> 00:34:33.620
to explain it extensively.

00:34:33.620 --> 00:34:43.320 position:56%
But, we've got to get there in terms
of how we choreograph Indian dance.

00:34:43.320 --> 00:34:48.860
And, there are ways to just enjoy
it without necessarily having

00:34:48.860 --> 00:34:53.740
to spell it out, and I
think it'll get there.

00:34:53.740 --> 00:34:55.040
&gt;&gt; Catherine Kerst: I
could imagine, you know,

00:34:55.040 --> 00:34:58.700 position:56%
I could imagine surtitles could
help, but they could also, in a way,

00:34:58.700 --> 00:35:03.110
come in the way of just responding.

00:35:03.110 --> 00:35:04.410
&gt;&gt; Anuradha Nehru: Yeah, so it--

00:35:04.410 --> 00:35:05.880 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Catherine Kerst: To the artistry.

00:35:05.880 --> 00:35:07.540
&gt;&gt; Anuradha Nehru: Yeah,
so that is a struggle.

00:35:07.540 --> 00:35:11.620
That is a struggle, and I
think surtitles should not be,

00:35:11.620 --> 00:35:15.510
should be used minimally
and not too extensively.

00:35:15.510 --> 00:35:20.290
Just to give context as
opposed to if it's overused,

00:35:20.290 --> 00:35:23.620
then the audience will be
reading rather than watching.

00:35:23.620 --> 00:35:28.190
And so, there has to be a fine
balance, and that's all part

00:35:28.190 --> 00:35:29.890
of the learning process, I think.

00:35:29.890 --> 00:35:32.110
&gt;&gt; Catherine Kerst:
That's fascinating.

00:35:32.110 --> 00:35:35.510
Could you speak a little
bit about the jewelry

00:35:35.510 --> 00:35:39.370
and the makeup and the costume?

00:35:39.370 --> 00:35:40.670
&gt;&gt; Anuradha Nehru: Yeah.

00:35:40.670 --> 00:35:41.970 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Catherine Kerst: For performance.

00:35:41.970 --> 00:35:43.590
It's a very distinctive costume.

00:35:43.590 --> 00:35:46.260
&gt;&gt; Anuradha Nehru: Yes, and
that's largely because of

00:35:46.260 --> 00:35:49.040
where Indian dance originated.

00:35:49.040 --> 00:35:55.300
It was a temple dance form,
and so it's pretty elaborate.

00:35:55.300 --> 00:36:00.080
But, the costuming and the
ornamentation is quite elaborate,

00:36:00.080 --> 00:36:06.590
has always been where the
dancer was seen as a devadasi

00:36:06.590 --> 00:36:15.050
or the dancer was dancing for
the gods and so was dressed

00:36:15.050 --> 00:36:18.460
in this fashion for that purpose.

00:36:18.460 --> 00:36:22.360
But, and we've, to a large extent,

00:36:22.360 --> 00:36:26.480
continued that tradition
of dressing.

00:36:26.480 --> 00:36:31.810
Although, in many more contemporary
Indian dance works today,

00:36:31.810 --> 00:36:36.970
you see a lot of simplification
to the ornamentation.

00:36:36.970 --> 00:36:43.650
And, I think it adds, it
adds to the dance form

00:36:43.650 --> 00:36:47.160
in certain contexts,
but it's not critical.

00:36:47.160 --> 00:36:49.760
I do believe it's not critical.

00:36:49.760 --> 00:36:54.210
I do believe we ourselves,
even at Kalanidhi have,

00:36:54.210 --> 00:36:57.840
when we've presented dances
which have more secular themes

00:36:57.840 --> 00:37:01.540
which are more social
themes, we've moved away

00:37:01.540 --> 00:37:07.310
from the very elaborate
costuming and ornamentation

00:37:07.310 --> 00:37:09.160
because it just doesn't go.

00:37:09.160 --> 00:37:14.590 position:56%
It does go with the more traditional
dancing, but not necessarily

00:37:14.590 --> 00:37:21.310
with the more social context,
contextual dances that we present.

00:37:21.310 --> 00:37:25.360 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Catherine Kerst: Do you have any
young men who are studying with you?

00:37:25.360 --> 00:37:27.340
&gt;&gt; Anuradha Nehru: This has
been another big challenge.

00:37:27.340 --> 00:37:32.330
I've had several boys start
learning dance and one

00:37:32.330 --> 00:37:37.210
or two became excellent, but
it's just tragic that all

00:37:37.210 --> 00:37:40.160
of my boy students give
up in middle school.

00:37:40.160 --> 00:37:41.460
&gt;&gt; Catherine Kerst: Yeah.

00:37:41.460 --> 00:37:43.420
&gt;&gt; Anuradha Nehru: The social
pressures are enormous,

00:37:43.420 --> 00:37:47.050
and it's tragic that
they all give up.

00:37:47.050 --> 00:37:52.230
So, it, no, I'm an all-female
dance company as of today.

00:37:52.230 --> 00:37:53.530
Yeah.

00:37:53.530 --> 00:37:54.830
&gt;&gt; Catherine Kerst: Yeah.

00:37:54.830 --> 00:37:56.130
So, in India, are there students?

00:37:56.130 --> 00:37:57.430
&gt;&gt; Anuradha Nehru: Yes.

00:37:57.430 --> 00:37:58.730
&gt;&gt; Catherine Kerst: Are
there male students?

00:37:58.730 --> 00:38:00.030
&gt;&gt; Anuradha Nehru: Yes, there are.

00:38:00.030 --> 00:38:03.360
But, still in the minority, but
there are several male students,

00:38:03.360 --> 00:38:07.410
and they're beautiful to watch.

00:38:07.410 --> 00:38:11.480
I brought two male dancers for
my production last weekend,

00:38:11.480 --> 00:38:15.650
one from India and one from
another part of the United States.

00:38:15.650 --> 00:38:18.550
It just adds-- because
there's a certain energy

00:38:18.550 --> 00:38:21.740
that male dancers bring
to Indian dance

00:38:21.740 --> 00:38:24.690 position:56%
that female dancers don't and can't.

00:38:24.690 --> 00:38:25.990
&gt;&gt; Catherine Kerst: Or together.

00:38:25.990 --> 00:38:27.290
&gt;&gt; Anuradha Nehru:
And, together, yeah.

00:38:27.290 --> 00:38:30.720
We dance together,
and it just adds a lot

00:38:30.720 --> 00:38:34.280
to the energy and to the dance.

00:38:34.280 --> 00:38:36.540
But, no, I haven't been successful.

00:38:36.540 --> 00:38:37.840
&gt;&gt; Catherine Kerst: No.

00:38:37.840 --> 00:38:42.290
I can imagine that it would
be very, very difficult.

00:38:42.290 --> 00:38:43.590
&gt;&gt; Anuradha Nehru: Yeah.

00:38:43.590 --> 00:38:47.790
&gt;&gt; Catherine Kerst: Has the dance
form changed as it becomes more

00:38:47.790 --> 00:38:50.910
of a woman's tradition, or?

00:38:50.910 --> 00:38:52.210
I just wonder because--

00:38:52.210 --> 00:38:53.510
&gt;&gt; Anuradha Nehru: Yeah.

00:38:53.510 --> 00:38:54.840
&gt;&gt; Catherine Kerst: It
seems like a huge change,

00:38:54.840 --> 00:38:56.800
did you say, in 75 years.

00:38:56.800 --> 00:38:58.600 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Anuradha Nehru: In 75 years, yes.

00:38:58.600 --> 00:39:00.630
I think it has changed.

00:39:00.630 --> 00:39:10.090
It's, there is definitely more
of the softer, graceful movements

00:39:10.090 --> 00:39:13.490
that you see more of a predominance

00:39:13.490 --> 00:39:20.520
of the more graceful movements
in our repertoire today.

00:39:20.520 --> 00:39:22.810
Although we haven't
given up on the vibrancy.

00:39:22.810 --> 00:39:24.380
I mean, that's the
beauty of Kuchipudi.

00:39:24.380 --> 00:39:25.680
&gt;&gt; Catherine Kerst: Oh, no.

00:39:25.680 --> 00:39:29.270
&gt;&gt; Anuradha Nehru: It has,
it has very vibrant, dynamic,

00:39:29.270 --> 00:39:35.430
strong movement vocabulary, but at
the same time, it has this very,

00:39:35.430 --> 00:39:38.430
very graceful, soft
movement as well.

00:39:38.430 --> 00:39:41.140
And, it is the confluence
of these two

00:39:41.140 --> 00:39:43.670
that make Kuchipudi
special, I think.

00:39:43.670 --> 00:39:49.850
And, and I think, just because it's
female practitioners, we, perhaps,

00:39:49.850 --> 00:39:55.110
it looks slightly different today
than it would have 75 years ago

00:39:55.110 --> 00:39:56.410
with an all-male dance form.

00:39:56.410 --> 00:40:01.310
&gt;&gt; Catherine Kerst: So, the
main gurus in India now,

00:40:01.310 --> 00:40:05.100
are they still male, or
are they also female?

00:40:05.100 --> 00:40:09.980
&gt;&gt; Anuradha Nehru: Yeah,
there's still a lot

00:40:09.980 --> 00:40:14.190
of male Kuchipudi gurus,
interestingly.

00:40:14.190 --> 00:40:22.960
We do have female teachers as
well, but still, in the village

00:40:22.960 --> 00:40:26.670
of Kuchipudi, for example,
today, we have mostly male gurus.

00:40:26.670 --> 00:40:27.970
&gt;&gt; Catherine Kerst: Really?

00:40:27.970 --> 00:40:29.270
I see.

00:40:29.270 --> 00:40:30.570
&gt;&gt; Anuradha Nehru:
Mostly, they're all male.

00:40:30.570 --> 00:40:34.590
Not to say that there aren't female
teachers elsewhere in the country,

00:40:34.590 --> 00:40:35.900
elsewhere in the country.

00:40:35.900 --> 00:40:40.200
In the cities, we have a
lot of female gurus, but,

00:40:40.200 --> 00:40:44.690
still in the heartland of
Kuchipudi, it's all male dominated.

00:40:44.690 --> 00:40:45.990
&gt;&gt; Catherine Kerst: Interesting.

00:40:45.990 --> 00:40:49.940
So, it was originally male
dominated where they performed as,

00:40:49.940 --> 00:40:52.160
they performed in women's roles.

00:40:52.160 --> 00:40:54.200
Now, it's reversed, in a sense.

00:40:54.200 --> 00:40:55.500
&gt;&gt; Anuradha Nehru: It is.

00:40:55.500 --> 00:40:58.170
&gt;&gt; Catherine Kerst: In your
school and in other contexts.

00:40:58.170 --> 00:40:59.470
&gt;&gt; Anuradha Nehru: It is.

00:40:59.470 --> 00:41:01.810
&gt;&gt; Catherine Kerst: Where they're,
the young women are portraying.

00:41:01.810 --> 00:41:03.400
&gt;&gt; Anuradha Nehru:
Portraying male characters.

00:41:03.400 --> 00:41:04.860
It's taken a full circle.

00:41:04.860 --> 00:41:06.160
&gt;&gt; Catherine Kerst: Yeah.

00:41:06.160 --> 00:41:07.460
Yeah.

00:41:07.460 --> 00:41:08.760
&gt;&gt; Anuradha Nehru: Yeah.

00:41:08.760 --> 00:41:10.320
&gt;&gt; Catherine Kerst: I understand
that there are different strains

00:41:10.320 --> 00:41:13.300
of Kuchipudi that are
currently taught.

00:41:13.300 --> 00:41:18.540
With Vempati how would
you characterize his,

00:41:18.540 --> 00:41:23.940
his distinctive expression
of Kuchipudi dance?

00:41:23.940 --> 00:41:25.240
&gt;&gt; Anuradha Nehru: I think

00:41:25.240 --> 00:41:35.390 position:56%
when Vempati Chinna Satyam has
definitely moved away from the style

00:41:35.390 --> 00:41:38.070
that he had learned in
the village of Kuchipudi.

00:41:38.070 --> 00:41:39.370
&gt;&gt; Catherine Kerst: Really?

00:41:39.370 --> 00:41:40.670
&gt;&gt; Anuradha Nehru: Yeah.

00:41:40.670 --> 00:41:47.240
He was hugely influenced by the
dance scene in Madras those days.

00:41:47.240 --> 00:41:54.480
He had moved to Chennai
in the '50s, 1950s,

00:41:54.480 --> 00:41:59.720
and Bharatanatyam there was a huge
revival of Bharatanatyam in Madras.

00:41:59.720 --> 00:42:03.750
So, I keep interchanging Madras
and Chennai because in the '50s,

00:42:03.750 --> 00:42:05.690
Madras, it was known as Madras.

00:42:05.690 --> 00:42:13.850 position:56%
It's today known as Chennai, but and
so, there was a lot of excitement

00:42:13.850 --> 00:42:17.810
with the revival of
Bharatanatyam in Madras.

00:42:17.810 --> 00:42:24.100
And so, he got to see a lot of
Bharatanatyam there in Madras

00:42:24.100 --> 00:42:27.180
and was influenced,
definitely, by it.

00:42:27.180 --> 00:42:40.410 position:56%
And, I think that definitely changed
his sense of aesthetics and he also,

00:42:40.410 --> 00:42:44.310
by introducing women
to the dance form,

00:42:44.310 --> 00:42:48.820
also the dance form did
change a little bit.

00:42:48.820 --> 00:42:58.060
And, he spent a lot of time
in removing certain aspects

00:42:58.060 --> 00:43:03.910
of the dance drama form that he
felt was not being received as well

00:43:03.910 --> 00:43:09.720
in Madras those days and
evolved the solo form in a way

00:43:09.720 --> 00:43:14.520
that was more appealing to
the audiences in Madras.

00:43:14.520 --> 00:43:16.660
And so, yes, Vempati
Chinna Satyam's style

00:43:16.660 --> 00:43:21.960 position:56%
of Kuchipudi is distinctly different
from the other guru's styles

00:43:21.960 --> 00:43:28.290
that you see even today,
both in India and abroad.

00:43:28.290 --> 00:43:33.330
And, it's very recognizable
difference to the dance,

00:43:33.330 --> 00:43:35.900
Indian classical dance aficionados.

00:43:35.900 --> 00:43:37.200
But, to a non --

00:43:37.200 --> 00:43:39.500
&gt;&gt; Catherine Kerst: How
would you describe it?

00:43:43.460 --> 00:43:47.360
&gt;&gt; Anuradha Nehru: So, it's, I
mean, without, it's much easier

00:43:47.360 --> 00:43:56.480 position:56%
to describe it with a demonstration,
but in words, I think, for example,

00:43:56.480 --> 00:44:02.990
he took away the whole
spoken, the dialogues.

00:44:02.990 --> 00:44:08.080
So, part of Kuchipudi tradition
was to have the spoken word

00:44:08.080 --> 00:44:10.460
as part of the production.

00:44:10.460 --> 00:44:14.610
Dancers would not only
come and sing on stage,

00:44:14.610 --> 00:44:16.430
but they would speak on stage.

00:44:16.430 --> 00:44:17.730
&gt;&gt; Catherine Kerst: Oh.

00:44:17.730 --> 00:44:19.120
&gt;&gt; Anuradha Nehru: So, it
was, it was very theatrical.

00:44:19.120 --> 00:44:23.250
So, there would be a lot
of drama as well as dance.

00:44:23.250 --> 00:44:27.170
They would, they would speak
as well as go and dance.

00:44:27.170 --> 00:44:28.790
So, they would do both,

00:44:28.790 --> 00:44:34.320
and Vempati's significant
intervention was

00:44:34.320 --> 00:44:39.630
to remove the spoken
word almost completely.

00:44:39.630 --> 00:44:43.980
He would, even if there
was the spoken word as part

00:44:43.980 --> 00:44:46.480
of the production, it
would be sung by a singer.

00:44:46.480 --> 00:44:50.470
It would not be recited or
sung or spoken by the dancer.

00:44:50.470 --> 00:44:54.510
So, that was definitely
a big change, and he,

00:44:54.510 --> 00:44:59.310
some would say he refined
the movements.

00:44:59.310 --> 00:45:02.170
Others would argue against it.

00:45:02.170 --> 00:45:06.390 position:56%
It depends on who you're talking to.

00:45:06.390 --> 00:45:10.310
And, I think his primary
contribution, also,

00:45:10.310 --> 00:45:15.990
has been to create
solo work which a lot

00:45:15.990 --> 00:45:21.910
of the other gurus
had not, have not.

00:45:21.910 --> 00:45:26.500
They've taken parts of the
dance drama, drama works,

00:45:26.500 --> 00:45:28.970
and they've presented as solos,

00:45:28.970 --> 00:45:33.660
but they have not independently
choreographed solos.

00:45:33.660 --> 00:45:34.960
&gt;&gt; Catherine Kerst: I see.

00:45:34.960 --> 00:45:36.260
&gt;&gt; Anuradha Nehru: Yeah.

00:45:36.260 --> 00:45:37.920
I'm talking about in
his time, not today.

00:45:37.920 --> 00:45:42.530
So, that was a huge difference
where a lot of his body

00:45:42.530 --> 00:45:51.580
of work had new solo dancers
created by him to poetry

00:45:51.580 --> 00:45:57.650
that extended beyond
the poems and the songs

00:45:57.650 --> 00:46:00.760
that were used traditionally
in the Kuchipudi village.

00:46:00.760 --> 00:46:04.500
And, he was the first
Kuchipudi guru that also,

00:46:04.500 --> 00:46:11.090
that also choreographed an entire
dance drama that had a social theme

00:46:11.090 --> 00:46:13.620
to it and not a religious
theme to it.

00:46:13.620 --> 00:46:18.790
He addressed the whole caste
system, based his production

00:46:18.790 --> 00:46:21.430
on Rabindranath Tagore's work.

00:46:21.430 --> 00:46:22.730
&gt;&gt; Catherine Kerst: Really?

00:46:22.730 --> 00:46:27.410
&gt;&gt; Anuradha Nehru: And, so he
had this incredible courage.

